Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg made his second of two appearances before Cong=
ress on Wednesday, enduring a five-hour session of questions from members o=
f the House Energy and Commerce Committee. (Here's the full transcript (htt=
ps://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2018/04/10/transcript-of-mar=
k-zuckerbergs-senate-hearing/?utm_term=3D.c1e1c6abd3b1).) In contrast to th=
eir amiably confused counterparts (https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/10/17222=
444/mark-zuckerberg-senate-hearing-highlights-cambridge-analytica) in the S=
enate, members of the House committee demonstrated a generally better comma=
nd of how Facebook works and how its efforts to develop richly detailed adv=
ertising profiles for billions of people have created privacy concerns arou=
nd the world. They were also punchy: there were lots of raised voices on We=
dnesday, and much more skepticism toward Mark Zuckerberg and Facebook gener=
ally.

As with yesterday, Facebook sought to promote steps it has already taken to=
 address the fallout of the Cambridge Analytica data privacy scandal. But H=
ouse members spent less time on Cambridge Analytica in favor of asking abou=
t a broader range of subjects, including how Facebook tracks people around =
the web, privacy protections for minors, and Facebook=E2=80=99s consent dec=
ree with the Federal Trade Commission.

Here are the seven most notable developments from today=E2=80=99s hearing.

Facebook made its clearest endorsement yet of bringing European privacy pro=
tections to people around the world. Facebook has offered mixed messages ov=
er the past week on whether it would abide by Europe=E2=80=99s General Data=
 Privacy Regulation, or GDPR, when it goes into effect in May. Today Zucker=
berg told Congress that yes, it would roll out GDPR-style protections globa=
lly (https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17224492/zuckerberg-facebook-congre=
ss-gdpr-data-protection). =E2=80=9CThe GDPR has a bunch of different import=
ant pieces,=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg told Rep. Janice Schakowsky (D-IL). =E2=80=
=9COne is offering controls over =E2=80=94 that we=E2=80=99re doing. The se=
cond is around pushing for affirmative consent and putting a control in fro=
nt of people that walks people through their choices. We=E2=80=99re going t=
o do that, too. ... We=E2=80=99re going to put a tool at the top of people=
=E2=80=99s apps that walks them through their setting.=E2=80=9D

Some representatives think Facebook has violated its consent decree with th=
e Federal Trade Commission. By the terms of a 2011 consent decree (https://=
www.ftc.gov/sites/default/files/documents/cases/2011/11/111129facebookagree=
.pdf), Facebook is required to identify and address emerging threats to use=
r privacy. Rep. Robert Latta (R-OH) was among several House members who int=
errogated Zuckerberg about whether Facebook had abided by its terms. =E2=80=
=9CWhy didn=E2=80=99t the audits that you had to submit under the FTC conse=
nt decree find these problems?=E2=80=9D Latta asked. Zuckerberg responded, =
to Latta and others, that Facebook believes it has complied with the decree.

Facebook is under pressure to explain how it tracks people around the web =
=E2=80=94 and why. Zuckerberg was asked repeatedly on Tuesday on how Facebo=
ok collects data from people as they navigate around the internet (https://=
www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17225482/facebook-shadow-profiles-zuckerberg-con=
gress-data-privacy?utm_campaign=3Dtheverge&amp;amp;utm_content=3Dchorus&amp=
;amp;utm_medium=3Dsocial&amp;amp;utm_source=3Dtwitter), whether or not they=
 have Facebook accounts or are logged into them. He was also asked how Face=
book stores data about which websites people visit, and whether it creates =
so-called =E2=80=9Cshadow profiles=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 accounts for people w=
ho either have not created Facebook accounts yet, or gotten rid of them.

Zuckerberg offered two explanations for tracking web behavior. One is secur=
ity =E2=80=94 if Facebook didn=E2=80=99t track people, he said, the platfor=
m couldn=E2=80=99t prevent someone from downloading every public Facebook p=
age. =E2=80=9CEven if someone isn=E2=80=99t logged in, we track certain inf=
ormation, like how many pages they=E2=80=99re accessing, as a security meas=
ure,=E2=80=9D he said. The other, of course, was ad targeting. =E2=80=9CWe =
may also collect information to make it so that those ads are more relevant=
 and work better on those websites,=E2=80=9D he said, adding that users can=
 opt out of ad targeting.

But under pressure from Rep. Ben Lujan (D-NM), Zuckerberg said he was not f=
amiliar with the =E2=80=9Cshadow profiles.=E2=80=9D (https://techcrunch.com=
/2018/04/11/facebook-shadow-profiles-hearing-lujan-zuckerberg/) He also cou=
ld not answer how many data points Facebook collects on the average user =
=E2=80=94 or non-user.

Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s own profile was part of the Cambridge Analytica data l=
eak. Among the millions of people whose data was improperly obtained by Cam=
bridge Analytica was the CEO himself (https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17=
224316/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-profile-cambridge-analytica-mydigitallife).=
 That revelation came thanks to a question from Rep. Anna Eschoo (D-CA). =
=E2=80=9CWas your data included in the data sold to malicious third parties=
?=E2=80=9D Eshoo asked. =E2=80=9CYour personal data?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYes,=
=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg answered. He didn=E2=80=99t offer any additional infor=
mation.

More members of Congress are pressing Facebook to offer additional privacy =
protections to minors. Yesterday, Zuckerberg faced questions over Messenger=
 Kids, his company=E2=80=99s app for chatting with children as young as 6. =
Today, Rep. Joe Barton (R-TX) pressed Zuckerberg to create new privacy prot=
ections for all minors. =E2=80=9CIs there any reason that we couldn=E2=80=
=99t have just a no-data-sharing policy, period, until you=E2=80=99re 18?=
=E2=80=9D Barton asked. =E2=80=9CNobody gets to scrape it; nobody gets to a=
ccess it. It=E2=80=99s absolutely, totally private. ... What=E2=80=99s wron=
g with that?=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg would not commit to adding additional priv=
acy protections. =E2=80=9CThe reality that we see is that teens often do wa=
nt to share their opinions publicly,=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg said =E2=80=94 sid=
estepping the question by conflating public posting by users with data coll=
ection on Facebook=E2=80=99s part.

Conservatives are trying to turn one page=E2=80=99s temporary suspension in=
to a cause c=C3=A9l=C3=A8bre. Republican House members repeatedly pressed Z=
uckerberg on the case (https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17225120/mark-zuc=
kerberg-facebook-congress-cruz-blackburn-diamond-silk) of Lynnette =E2=80=
=9CDiamond=E2=80=9D Hardaway and Rochelle =E2=80=9CSilk=E2=80=9D Richardson=
, two pro-Trump vloggers who were told their content was =E2=80=9Cunsafe to=
 the community.=E2=80=9D The sisters have alleged that Facebook has prevent=
ed them from notifying their followers about new posts and throttled their =
reach. (It=E2=80=99s not clear how much of that is directed at the vloggers=
, and how much is related to recent changes to Facebook=E2=80=99s News Feed=
 algorithm.) =E2=80=9CLet me tell you something right now,=E2=80=9D said Re=
p. Marsha Blackburn (R-TN). =E2=80=9CDiamond and Silk is not terrorism.=E2=
=80=9D Zuckerberg said the page had been deemed unsafe in error.

Congress wants Facebook to do more to fight opioid sales online. People sel=
l just about everything using Facebook ads, and that includes opioids (http=
s://www.wired.com/story/one-woman-got-facebook-to-police-opioid-sales-on-in=
stagram). Even though drug sales are against Facebook=E2=80=99s terms =E2=
=80=94 not to mention illegal =E2=80=94 several representatives reported th=
at drug dealers were slipping through the cracks. =E2=80=9CYour platform is=
 still being used to circumvent the law, and allow people to buy highly add=
ictive drugs without a prescription,=E2=80=9D said Rep. David McKinley, (R-=
WV). =E2=80=9CWith all due respect, Facebook is actually enabling an illega=
l activity and, in so doing, you are hurting people.=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg sa=
id the company would try to improve its content moderation team. =E2=80=9CI=
 think that there are a number of areas of content that we need to do a bet=
ter job policing on our service,=E2=80=9D he said.

