C9-2Fj4XC8c2QUjXE" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">Here=E2=80=99=
s the full transcript</a>.) In contrast to their <a href=3D"http://em.getre=
vue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw/h3/SZrPzbQR0Tj0WaBKLu=
6ypbI9duC2WdF1dtCx90kfbSFGq0ezOcuus9pEBSl4TwIiYYHd5ezJwTTLldnvdA-2BBOVGLwPx=
7I44nYb6kSuia-2Fev7DqhIQXZ4qCjcXLnDCOIlNKh9n1xiLnrCJDSPN0sFlw-3D-3D" style=
=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">amiably confused counterparts</a> in =
the Senate, members of the House committee demonstrated a generally better =
command of how Facebook works and how its efforts to develop richly detaile=
d advertising profiles for billions of people have created privacy concerns=
 around the world. They were also punchy: there were lots of raised voices =
on Wednesday, and much more skepticism toward Mark Zuckerberg and Facebook =
generally.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">As with yesterd=
ay, Facebook sought to promote steps it has already taken to address the fa=
llout of the Cambridge Analytica data privacy scandal. But House members sp=
ent less time on Cambridge Analytica in favor of asking about a broader ran=
ge of subjects, including how Facebook tracks people around the web, privac=
y protections for minors, and Facebook=E2=80=99s consent decree with the Fe=
deral Trade Commission.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">He=
re are the seven most notable developments from today=E2=80=99s hearing.</d=
iv><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>Facebook made its clearest endorsement yet of bringing European privacy =
protections to people around the world.</b> Facebook has offered mixed mess=
ages over the past week on whether it would abide by Europe=E2=80=99s Gener=
al Data Privacy Regulation, or GDPR, when it goes into effect in May. Today=
 Zuckerberg told Congress that yes, <a href=3D"http://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c=
/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw/h4/SZrPzbQR0Tj0WaBKLu6ypbI9duC2WdF=
1dtCx90kfbSG5qsTvPt72gHBiFkjwhxvS5vitJRRXGwAeyXJ9TSsT28S2Giq05qb3vQ8zwcFwGQ=
acryvebgEnpLJuCRmqmNFJ" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">it would=
 roll out GDPR-style protections globally</a>. =E2=80=9CThe GDPR has a bunc=
h of different important pieces,=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg told Rep. Janice Schak=
owsky (D-IL). =E2=80=9COne is offering controls over =E2=80=94 that we=E2=
=80=99re doing. The second is around pushing for affirmative consent and pu=
tting a control in front of people that walks people through their choices.=
 We=E2=80=99re going to do that, too. =E2=80=A6 We=E2=80=99re going to put =
a tool at the top of people=E2=80=99s apps that walks them through their se=
tting.=E2=80=9D</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>Some representatives think Facebook has violated its consent decree with=
 the Federal Trade Commission.</b> By the terms of <a href=3D"http://em.get=
revue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw/h5/P3vqik9L7Miip2dq=
1PtJ-2F107RLVDG-2B3gGBz3Vsrq0k2SorY6sIu5wZ1V2zyEIA78E1hojP0SKvsSfxAYPXNFyKI=
Ah5aQz7HDxobBXl84MZLRZSqRM4wM4E82zYGDTxD0" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=
=3D"_blank">a 2011 consent decree</a>, Facebook is required to identify and=
 address emerging threats to user privacy. Rep. Robert Latta (R-OH) was amo=
ng several House members who interrogated Zuckerberg about whether Facebook=
 had abided by its terms. =E2=80=9CWhy didn=E2=80=99t the audits that you h=
ad to submit under the FTC consent decree find these problems?=E2=80=9D Lat=
ta asked. Zuckerberg responded, to Latta and others, that Facebook believes=
 it has complied with the decree.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"r=
evue-p">
<b>Facebook is under pressure to explain how it tracks people around the we=
b =E2=80=94 and why.</b> Zuckerberg was asked repeatedly on Tuesday on <a h=
ref=3D"http://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw=
/h6/SZrPzbQR0Tj0WaBKLu6ypbI9duC2WdF1dtCx90kfbSHypf5d3-2FhOeby6fqry10QfjiWVA=
cF9UFwRnT9-2B3GLKgSy50MsVnYbYusbKyZqV4emF7NtZEWOJN3y8Z9tpL4sDpiqVKse-2F60BS=
FWJYTExfvyNmpt6AIIQLFYDv4lwdr29icrNWlY4nRWUwuEii8krC6sTwCmQud22vUuWvN6Zk6Sw=
e42DJv3NX-2FKTBDKEu5Biaw51suECvRrIFmHSttoZs" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" targe=
t=3D"_blank">how Facebook collects data from people as they navigate around=
 the internet</a>, whether or not they have Facebook accounts or are logged=
 into them. He was also asked how Facebook stores data about which websites=
 people visit, and whether it creates so-called =E2=80=9Cshadow profiles=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94 accounts for people who either have not created Facebook a=
ccounts yet, or gotten rid of them.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D=
"revue-p">Zuckerberg offered two explanations for tracking web behavior. On=
e is security =E2=80=94 if Facebook didn=E2=80=99t track people, he said, t=
he platform couldn=E2=80=99t prevent someone from downloading every public =
Facebook page. =E2=80=9CEven if someone isn=E2=80=99t logged in, we track c=
ertain information, like how many pages they=E2=80=99re accessing, as a sec=
urity measure,=E2=80=9D he said. The other, of course, was ad targeting. =
=E2=80=9CWe may also collect information to make it so that those ads are m=
ore relevant and work better on those websites,=E2=80=9D he said, adding th=
at users can opt out of ad targeting.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=
=3D"revue-p">But under pressure from Rep. Ben Lujan (D-NM), Zuckerberg said=
 <a href=3D"http://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8=
pNTZw/h7/uxy1oodU7sc9xqxBp79HlWwJztr3xKA-2BCT9GTv-2BJ1na40YHtEz3lgOtmE3pZuo=
h-2BL-2BYmxVDu5tduBZn4bCn23ad1iuJO3ILoZFbOP2xLegi0OXA3AnKCO1F1iFGEEsHx" sty=
le=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">he was not familiar with the =E2=80=
=9Cshadow profiles.=E2=80=9D</a> He also could not answer how many data poi=
nts Facebook collects on the average user =E2=80=94 or non-user.</div><div =
style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>Zuckerberg=E2=80=99s own profile was part of the Cambridge Analytica dat=
a leak.</b> Among the millions of people whose data was improperly obtained=
 by Cambridge Analytica <a href=3D"http://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/=
t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw/h8/SZrPzbQR0Tj0WaBKLu6ypbI9duC2WdF1dtCx90kfbSE=
-2Fu698v8wY22eAU-2FMUNnJ-2FoG3Cm1DFfMkd2v303W-2FMy-2FJ8S8goUqad4K-2BTVs9gW-=
2ByMZrU-2FjW1YPxrz9LtOXe6-2FjtrZ-2F29grvTB0VXCr6nrdg-3D-3D" style=3D"color:=
 #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">was the CEO himself</a>. That revelation came t=
hanks to a question from Rep. Anna Eschoo (D-CA). =E2=80=9CWas your data in=
cluded in the data sold to malicious third parties?=E2=80=9D Eshoo asked. =
=E2=80=9CYour personal data?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYes,=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg ans=
wered. He didn=E2=80=99t offer any additional information.</div><div style=
=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>More members of Congress are pressing Facebook to offer additional priva=
cy protections to minors</b>. Yesterday, Zuckerberg faced questions over Me=
ssenger Kids, his company=E2=80=99s app for chatting with children as young=
 as 6. Today, Rep. Joe Barton (R-TX) pressed Zuckerberg to create new priva=
cy protections for all minors. =E2=80=9CIs there any reason that we couldn=
=E2=80=99t have just a no-data-sharing policy, period, until you=E2=80=99re=
 18?=E2=80=9D Barton asked. =E2=80=9CNobody gets to scrape it; nobody gets =
to access it. It=E2=80=99s absolutely, totally private. =E2=80=A6 What=E2=
=80=99s wrong with that?=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg would not commit to adding add=
itional privacy protections. =E2=80=9CThe reality that we see is that teens=
 often do want to share their opinions publicly,=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg said =
=E2=80=94 sidestepping the question by conflating public posting by users w=
ith data collection on Facebook=E2=80=99s part.</div><div style=3D"margin: =
0;" class=3D"revue-p">
<b>Conservatives are trying to turn one page=E2=80=99s temporary suspension=
 into a cause c=C3=A9l=C3=A8bre.</b> Republican House members <a href=3D"ht=
tp://em.getrevue.co/mpss/c/CwE/1EoYAA/t.2gk/E5K7h_MjTT22WlGY8pNTZw/h9/SZrPz=
bQR0Tj0WaBKLu6ypbI9duC2WdF1dtCx90kfbSFjNMWrEk4hoQyeUJqLc3K1aEs771XJ3fqDVj36=
Phf87LEnA4MPq0pn0x8B2BQS636uRrXyTYmeRfPaazCeKe8-2FTvOKzJrUqWGaD8eDZLly-2Fw-=
3D-3D" style=3D"color: #8b9dc3" target=3D"_blank">repeatedly pressed Zucker=
berg on the case</a> of Lynnette =E2=80=9CDiamond=E2=80=9D Hardaway and Roc=
helle =E2=80=9CSilk=E2=80=9D Richardson, two pro-Trump vloggers who were to=
ld their content was =E2=80=9Cunsafe to the community.=E2=80=9D The sisters=
 have alleged that Facebook has prevented them from notifying their followe=
rs about new posts and throttled their reach. (It=E2=80=99s not clear how m=
uch of that is directed at the vloggers, and how much is related to recent =
changes to Facebook=E2=80=99s News Feed algorithm.) =E2=80=9CLet me tell yo=
u something right now,=E2=80=9D said Rep. Marsha Blackburn (R-TN). =E2=80=
=9CDiamond and Silk is not terrorism.=E2=80=9D Zuckerberg said the page had=
 been deemed unsafe in error.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0;" class=3D"revue=
-p">
<b>Congress wants Facebook to do more to fight opioid sales online.</b> Peo=
